      <h2 style = 'color: white; font-family: Optima; font-size: 18px'>What does too much Carbon Dioxide do to our atmosphere?</h2>
      <p style = 'color: white; font-family: Optima; font-size: 16px'>Ever since industrialization began, carbon dioxide levels have been rising. Through combustion, burning fossils for gas and even to power our homes, we have relied on carbon for so many things. The problem with this over reliance on carbon means that more than necessary carbon is released into the atmosphere in the form of gas: carbon dioxide. Through photsynthesis, plants remove this carbon dioxide from the atmosphere to produce energy, but we are burning these plants, releasing that carbon dioxide back into the atmosphere. This in turn hurts the planet, as carbon dioxide gas increases the global temperature to levels higher than normal.<br><br> Carbon dioxide, in the atmosphere, absorbs heat and releases it in every direction. So, more carbon dioxide means a warmer planet. Some of the many effects of excess carbon dioxide in the atmosphere include: </p>
      <ul style='color: white; font-family: Optima'>
        <li>Higher temperatures</li>
        <li>Extreme Weather: Droughts, Floods, Wildfires</li>
        <li>Increased Ocean Acidification: Leads to Sea Animals Dying</li>
        <li>Respiratory Diseases</li>
        <li>Species Extinction</li>
      </ul>
      <p><br><br></p>
      <div style='display: flex; gap: 60px'>
        <img style='height: 160px; width: 320px' src="co2_rate.jpg">
        <p style='color: white; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: 16px'>This graph shows Carbon Dioxide Emissions in the United States from 1751 to 2017.<br>Notice how emissions before industrialization were at around 0 tons and have rapidly increased over the years.</p>
